TI  - Subpopulation-specific synthetic electronic health records can increase mortality prediction performance
AU  - Perets, Oriel
AU  - Rappoport, Nadav
T2  - JAMIA OPEN
AB  - Objective To address biased representation in Electronic Health Records (EHRs) across subpopulations (SPs), which leads to predictive models underperforming for underrepresented groups, we propose a framework to enhance equitable predictive performance.Materials and Methods We developed a framework using generative adversarial networks (GANs) to create SP-specific synthetic data, which augments the original training datasets. Subsequently, we employed an ensemble approach, training distinct prediction models tailored to each SP.Results The proposed framework was evaluated on two datasets derived from the MIMIC database, achieving a performance improvement in Receiver Operating Characteristics Area Under Curve (ROCAUC) ranging from 8% to 31% for underrepresented SPs.Discussion The results indicate that targeted synthetic data augmentation and SP-specific model training significantly mitigate the performance disparities observed in conventional predictive models trained on imbalanced EHR data.Conclusion Our novel GAN-based framework, combined with an ensemble prediction approach, effectively enhances predictive equity across SPs. The code and ensemble models developed in this study are publicly available, supporting further research and practical adoption of equitable predictive analytics in healthcare. Healthcare data collected in hospitals often show bias. This means that some groups of patients-like those from certain ethnic backgrounds-are underrepresented in the data. As a result, machine learning models trained on these data may not work as well for those underrepresented groups. In this study, we developed a method to help make these models more fair. We used a type of artificial intelligence called a generative adversarial network (GAN) to create synthetic data that resemble real patients. For each underrepresented group, we generated additional synthetic data and added them to the training set. We then trained separate models for each group. Our method was tested on two real-world hospital datasets and showed improved prediction accuracy-especially for those groups that originally had fewer records. This approach helps ensure that predictive tools used in healthcare work more equally for everyone, regardless of their background. The method and code are freely available to support broader use of equitable AI in medical research.
