TI  - Data-centric federated learning for neuro-oncology: Addressing heterogeneity via privacy-preserving generative augmentation
AU  - Li, Zhengkun
AU  - Dib, Omar
AU  - Li, Shiyun
T2  - ENGINEERING APPLICATIONS OF ARTIFICIAL IN℡LIGENCE
AB  - Federated Learning (FL) offers a decentralized paradigm for multi-class brain tumor classification using Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI), yet its clinical deployment is challenged by data scarcity, statistical heterogeneity (i.e., non-independent and identically distributed (non-IID) data), and strict privacy regulations. Standard FL algorithms often diverge under extreme single-class client partitions common in specialized medical centers. To address these barriers, we propose a robust, data-centric FL framework that bridges algorithmic limitations and clinical reality. The framework introduces a three-tier protocol: (i) an independent and identically distributed (IID) baseline; (ii) a Hybrid Federated Learning (Hybrid-FL) strategy using minimal shared clinical data to establish realistic performance upper bounds; and (iii) a Synthetic Federated Learning (Synthetic-FL) strategy leveraging Latent Diffusion Models (LDMs) for strictly privacy-preserving data augmentation. To mitigate confirmation bias in synthetic generation, we implement a multi-dimensional quality assurance protocol validating anatomical fidelity and diversity via Kernel Inception Distance (KID) and Learned Perceptual Image Patch Similarity (LPIPS) metrics. Experimental results on a large multi-institutional dataset (N= 7,023) show that Hybrid-FL achieves high diagnostic accuracy (approximate to 95%) with only 10% shared holdout data, while fully privacy-preserving Synthetic-FL recovers substantial performance (> 83%) from a baseline of non-convergence without exposing patient records. Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping (Grad-CAM) confirms that the global model consistently captures robust pathological features across heterogeneous clients. This study quantitatively characterizes the privacy-utility trade-off and provides a scalable, interpretable engineering solution for collaborative neuro-oncology.
