TI  - The application of deep learning studies in cancer diagnosis
AU  - Huang, Huan
A2  - S, Gorlatch
AB  - Deep learning holds potential for cancer diagnosis yet encounters obstacles prior to its regular application in clinical settings. The primary barriers consist of overfitting, dataset bias, and insufficient external validation. In this work, we first review existing methods, typical pitfalls, and practical guidelines, then present a straightforward CNN designed for binary tumor classification using synthetic H&E-stained images. We also summarize unsupervised feature learning approaches and major model categories-including CNNs, GANs, autoencoders, RNNs/LSTMs, and multiscale or MIL-CNNs-and put forward recommendations for preregistered protocols, multi-institutional external validation, and large-scale, diverse training cohorts. Our lightweight PyTorch-based model employs convolution-pooling blocks, adaptive pooling, and a compact linear head; it was trained with data augmentation and selected based on the lowest validation loss. When tested on an independent dataset, this model attained an accuracy of 97.5%, along with a malignant precision of 1.000 and recall of 0.950 (corresponding to one false negative and zero false positives), and no obvious overfitting was observed. Although CNNs can deliver strong performance in image-based diagnostic tasks, results obtained from small-scale synthetic datasets call for strict external verification. Directions for future research include transfer learning, model ensembling, larger multicenter datasets, and interpretable tools such as Grad-CAM. © 2025 COPYRIGHT SPIE.
