TI  - ARTIFICIAL IN℡LIGENCE: Al-DOOM OR BLOOM? THE MEDICOLEGAL AND ETHICAL IMPLICATIONS FOR HEALTH
AU  - Loh, Erwin
T2  - Medicine and Law
AB  - The role of healthcare professionals has changed over history because of emerging technologies, and the rise of artificial intelligence (AI) in health is right now bringing a transformational change to how care is being provided. Al is proving to be better than humans in big data synthesis and image pattern recognition, with implications for diagnostic specialties such as pathology or radiology. This revolution brings new ethical and medicolegal challenges to the healthcare system and to the health professions. As Al automates diagnosis formulation and surgical procedures, the question of who the final clinical decision-maker is, and therefore who should be held accountable if things go wrong, becomes challenging. This conundrum has implications for liability, intellectual property, and privacy and confidentiality. The way Al uses deep learning methodologies also raises the risk of bias. The need for ethical guidelines for the development and use of Al in health is discussed, as well as local and national governance frameworks. © 2022, William S. Hein & Co., Inc.. All rights reserved.
