TI  - A Survey on Synthetic Data Generation for Diabetes Applications
AU  - S.Gokulraj, K. Sathyaseelan; S. Sarathambekai; R. Senthilkumar;
T2  - 2025 IEEE 9th International Conference on Information and Communication Technology (CICT)
AB  - Synthetic data is increasingly used in diabetes research for solving limited data availability, class imbalance, and patient privacy concerns. This review examines methods for generating synthetic data. It is categorized into four main groups like statistical methods, machine learning approaches, deep learning models and hybrid or emerging frameworks. The use of synthetic data is described across several diabetes related applications. Including electronic health records, continuous glucose monitoring time-series data, medical imaging, decision support systems and data augmentation for predictive modeling. Common real and synthetic datasets were reviewed, highlighting their strengths, weakness and relevance for diabetes studies. The evaluation strategies are reviewed, particularly on data fidelity, model performance and privacy preservation. Several challenges still need to be addressed. This include verifying the reliability of synthetic data and reducing the bias within algorithms. In addition, compliance with regulations like HIPAA and GDPR must be maintained while ensuring the solutions remain practical for real world use. The review highlights several directions for future research. These include advancing generative models and developing personalized with cross domain synthetic data. It also highlights the need for clear ethical and regulatory guidelines to ensure responsible use in clinical settings.
