AU  - Lu, J. Duan; H. Jing; F.
T2  - 2025 IEEE 7th International Conference on Artificial Intelligence, Computer Science, and Information Processing (AICSIP)
AB  - Disease prediction (DP) requires an automatic program to infer a patient's underlying diseases from his/her electronic medical records (EMRs), a long-standing focus in bioinformatics. Although deep learning approaches have achieved promising results on this task, the lack of sufficient clinical EMRs significantly prohibits further progress. In this paper, we exploit advanced technologies encompassing pre-trained language models (PLMs) to address this problem. We first reformulate DP as a masked language modeling problem, which facilitates BERT, with slight fine-tuning, to jointly predict the assertion words that indicate the diagnostic opinion of candidate diseases. We also leverage the excellent generation ability of GPT-4, reprocessing abundant online medical texts to augment the limited EMR data. For this, we ask GPT-4 to synthesize novel EMRs using medical cases and dialogues that contain partial clinical information by performing a Grouped Pointwise MixUp algorithm. To utilize the synthetic data without suffering potential biases, we establish criteria and prompt GPT-4 to filter out flawed samples through knowledge-based question-answering and use the remaining to fine-tune BERT through noise-tolerant training. Extensive evaluation results on two real datasets demonstrate substantial enhancements achieved by our methods. Our codes and data will be released to facilitate further studies.
