AU  - Muslih, N. W. Wulansari; M. A. Soeleman; C. Supriyanto;
T2  - 2025 International Seminar on Application for Technology of Information and Communication (iSemantic)
AB  - Skin cancer is a disease that is increasingly common and can have serious consequences if not detected early. In an effort to support medical image-based diagnosis, the development of automated classification models with artificial intelligence is growing. However, the main challenge often faced is the imbalance of data between classes, where the number of images of certain types of cancer is much less than others. This study proposes the use of the SMOTE-RENN method, a combined oversampling and noise reduction technique, to balance the training data before the classification process is performed. The dataset used comes from dermatoscopic images sourced from HAM10000, and the classification process is performed using a deep learning architecture approach: CNN, ResNet50, and DenseNet121. Test results show that the application of SMOTE-RENN consistently improves model performance. Evaluation using metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score reinforces that this approach is able to provide more stable and accurate results. Results show that the highest accuracy, precision, recall and F1-score values are 99% in the resnet and densenet models. Thus, this method has the potential to support a more reliable and fair automated skin cancer detection system for all disease categories.
