TI  - Attention-Augmented Generative AdversarialNetworks (GANs) for Synthetic Data Augmentationin Prostate Cancer MRI-Bases Segmentation Tasks
AU  - S, K. A; M. Y; N. Kumar
T2  - 2025 2nd International Conference on Artificial Intelligence and Knowledge Discovery in Concurrent Engineering (ICECONF)
AB  - Prostate cancer remains to be one of the most common cancers in men. Detection and segmentation of this cancer from MRI images are very important for patient outcomes. The work in this project introduces a novel method utilizing attention-augmented GANs in generating synthetic data for the specific application of prostate cancer MRI segmentation. By integrating multi-scale U-Net models with channel-attention and spatial-attention mechanisms, the system generates high-fidelity mpMRI images representing patterns of interest for prostate cancer. A two-attention discriminator and Wasserstein adversarial training ensure anatomical fidelity and diversity of the synthesized data, addressing data scarcity and enhancing segmentation model strength. In reality, a segmentation network that integrates synthetic data and attention-based subnetworks demonstrates remarkable gains in correctly delineating tumors, particularly in challenging and complex cases. Quality assurance entails detailed quantitative evaluations, radiologist-led assessments, and statistical reviews to ensure the clinical significance and reliability of the synthetic data set. The methodology involves curriculum learning, uncertainty estimations, and interpretability tools that enable reliable model predictions and expert reviews efficiently. Overall, this project establishes a technique for synthetic data augmentation based on advances in adversarial and attention learning in recent times, resulting in improved prostate MRI segmentation and offering a useful resource to improve prostate cancer screening and diagnosis.
