TI  - The Effect of Vertebral Bone Attenuation on Measured Spinal Cord Activity in PET/MRI
AU  - Tsoumpas, E. Lennie; S. Sourbron; N. Hoggard; C.
T2  - 2023 IEEE Nuclear Science Symposium, Medical Imaging Conference and International Symposium on Room-Temperature Semiconductor Detectors (NSS MIC RTSD)
AB  - Vertebral bone attenuation is typically ignored in image reconstruction for PET/MRI, but there is a risk that this biases the measured tracer uptake in the spinal cord. The aim of this study is to investigate this issue using patient data and simulations in an anthropomorphic phantom. Data in 2 patients administered 200MBq [18F]FDG were acquired on GE Signa PET/MR scanner to a 2 bed position static PET acquisition protocol with simultaneous MRI. Patient images were reconstructed with a Time of Flight OSEM Algorithm (2 iterations, 28 subsets, 2.3x2.3x2.78mm voxel size). Simulated data was created with the XCAT phantom representing the physiological [18F]FDG uptake of the neck and thorax. Simulated sinogram data were reconstructed in SIRF using an OSEM algorithm (10 iterations, 28 subsets, 2x2x2.78mm voxel size) with an accurate reference attenuation map and again using an attenuation map modified to assign tissue values to all bones. Data in both patients showed a sharp and consistent 46%-53% decline in activity at the transition from the cervical to the thoracic spine. This effect was not observed in simulated data with correct bone densities. When bone was incorrectly assigned tissue densities, a similar drop in the uptake was observed, but at 8.1% for mean uptake (20.1% for maximum uptake) this was substantially weaker than in the patient data. We conclude that while the spinal cord clearly shows an unphysiological decline in uptake values when acquired in PET/MRI, this can only partly be explained by ignoring attenuation in bone.
