AU  - L, C. Chakravorty; N. S. Shaik Khaji; M. A. A. Shaikh; D. T.
T2  - 2025 9th International Conference on Computational System and Information Technology for Sustainable Solutions (CSITSS)
AB  - Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) have emerged as a trans formative framework in addressing the persistent challenge of data scarcity within machine learning. Unlike conventional augmentation methods, which mainly manipulate existing samples, GANs are capable of generating synthetic data that captures the true statistical structure of the training distribution. This study not only reviews their evolution and application across modalities such as images, natural language, and audio but also provides a synthesized comparison of empirical results reported in recent literature. A taxonomy of GAN approaches for augmentation is introduced, mapping different architectures to real-world data challenges such as imbalance, privacy, and fairness. The work highlights concrete contributions including a unified comparison framework, an evaluation of technical advancements, and identification of research gaps. In doing so, it positions GAN s as a critical enabler of scalable, ethical, and high-performing machine learning systems.
