TY  - JOUR
TI  - Improving LightGBM Performance in Diabetes Risk Prediction Using Fi-Guide SMOTE
AU  - Borman, A. Sah; A. M. Tanniewa; D. Puspita; Y. Jusman; R. I.
T2  - 2025 International Conference on Information Technology and Computing (ICITCOM)
AB  - Class imbalance between diabetic and non-diabetic patients remains a major challenge in medical risk classification tasks, often leading machine learning models to become biased toward the majority class and fail to accurately identify positive cases. This study proposes a diabetes risk classification model based on the Light Gradient Boosting Machine (LightGBM) algorithm, integrated with an information-guided oversampling technique named Feature Importance Guided SMOTE (Fi-Guide SMOTE). The proposed method aims to address data imbalance by generating synthetic minority samples based on each feature's contribution to the classification outcome. The dataset consists of 2,000 patient records with nine clinical features, and has undergone preprocessing steps including missing value imputation, normalization, and outlier filtering. Model performance was evaluated across three scenarios: baseline (without oversampling), standard SMOTE, and Fi-Guide SMOTE, using accuracy, recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC as the primary evaluation metrics. Experimental results show that the LightGBM + Fi-Guide SMOTE model improves classification performance, with an F1-score of 97.45% for the diabetes class and an overall accuracy of 98.25%. Although the numerical improvement is relatively small, it has meaningful implications in medical contexts where accurate early detection is critical. These findings indicate that information-guided oversampling can enhance model reliability on imbalanced medical datasets.
