TY  - JOUR
TI  - A Survey on Speech Emotion Recognition Datasets: Research Challenges, Issues and Opportunities
AU  - Sharma, N. Chaubey; L. Singh; H.
T2  - 2025 International Conference on Innovations and Emerging Technologies In AI & Communication Systems (IETACS)
AB  - Speech Emotion Recognition (SER)has attracted a lot of interest due to its uses in emotional computing, education, healthcare, and human-computer interaction. However, the constraints of accessible audio datasets severely limit the advancement of SER. Model generalization is constrained by the majority of extant corpora, short sample sizes, lack of speaker diversity, class imbalance, and language or cultural bias. The resilience of trained models in practical situations is further affected by environmental variables such as channel fluctuation, recording quality, and background noise. These issues show how urgently large scale, balanced, multilingual datasets, as well as consistent labeling systems and evaluation processes, are needed. This paper presents a survey of speech emotion recognition datasets along with research challenges and issues. Speech data sets are taxonomized according to how emotional expressions are obtained, mainly into four categories: simulated data set, prompted data set, unprompted data set, and natural dataset. Moreover, it describes various research challenges and issues that need attention to develop precise, reliable, and broadly applicable SER systems. Data set-related problems can be facilitated via data augmentation, cross corpus learning, multi-modal integration, and transfer learning.
