TI  - Bridging Research and Practice: A Systematic Review of Deep Learning Techniques in Medical Imaging
AU  - Vijai Singh, Prerna Bhardwaj, Shruti Arora, Disha Singhal
T2  - Archives of Computational Methods in Engineering
AB  - Medical Image Analysis plays a critical role in modern healthcare by enabling accurate, efficient, and non-invasive diagnosis. With the rise of Deep Learning (DL), particularly Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), automated medical imaging has achieved remarkable advances in segmentation, detection, and classification tasks. This literature survey provides a comprehensive review of 86 recent studies applying DL models—including CNNs, U-Net, GANs, and Transformers—across multiple imaging modalities such as MRI, CT, and X-ray. We systematically examine the performance, strengths, and limitations of these approaches, with an emphasis on clinical relevance and translational challenges. Furthermore, we critically assess evaluation methodologies and identify key gaps that must be addressed for widespread clinical adoption. Our findings offer a structured roadmap for future research and development in DL-powered medical imaging, aiming to bridge the gap between research innovation and real-world healthcare applications.
