TY  - JOUR
TI  - Artificial Intelligence Methods for Clean Energy and Environmental Engineering Systems: A Cross-Sectoral Computational Review
AU  - Chukwuebuka Joseph Ejiyi, Olusola O. Bamisile, Danny Love Wamba Djukem, Chidinma N. Diokpo, Francis O. Eze, Gladys W. Muoka, Francis Sam, Qingxian Zhang, Dongsheng Cai, Abena A. Atwereboannah, Joel Victor Dossa
T2  - Archives of Computational Methods in Engineering
AB  - Artificial intelligence (AI) is rapidly becoming a central computational paradigm for advancing clean energy and environmental engineering systems. Beyond incremental performance gains, AI introduces new methods for modeling, optimization, and decision support across complex, multi-scale systems. Existing reviews have largely examined isolated application areas such as renewable forecasting, smart grids, or carbon capture, resulting in fragmented insights into methodological progress. This review addresses this gap by providing a cross-sectoral computational synthesis of more than 300 studies, offering one of the most comprehensive assessments of AI methods applied to clean energy and environmental engineering to date. We systematically examine AI-driven approaches across renewable energy systems, energy storage, hydrogen and bioenergy pathways, carbon capture, utilization, and storage (CCUS), and recycling within circular economy frameworks. Particular emphasis is placed on computational methods that integrate machine learning (ML), deep learning (DL), reinforcement learning (RL), and physics-informed models with lifecycle assessment (LCA) and techno-economic analysis (TEA), thereby linking algorithmic innovation to system-level sustainability, cost efficiency, and engineering feasibility. Beyond documenting methodological advances, we analyze persistent challenges, including data scarcity, model generalization, interpretability, algorithmic bias, cybersecurity vulnerabilities, and the integration of AI with legacy infrastructure. We further assess the environmental footprint of AI itself, highlighting the energy and carbon costs associated with large-scale model training. The review also proposes a forward-looking roadmap centered on open and interoperable datasets, physics-informed and explainable AI, robust governance frameworks, and closer alignment between computational methods, policy instruments, and market mechanisms. By unifying methods across sectors, this review positions AI as a foundational enabler of resilient, equitable, and sustainable clean energy and environmental engineering systems.
DA  - 2026///
PY  - 2026
