TI  - Advances in Machine Learning and Deep Learning for Hormonal Disorder Diagnosis: an Exhaustive Review on PCOS, Thyroid, and Optimization Techniques
AU  - Sanjay Dhanka, Elakkiya Rajasekar, Ankur Kumar, Abhinav Sharma, Haswanth Vundavilli, Surita Maini
T2  - Archives of Computational Methods in Engineering
AB  - Hormonal disorders like Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS), thyroid dysfunction, and diabetes pose significant diagnostic challenges due to their complex etiology and overlapping symptoms. Traditional methods relying on static biomarkers and subjective assessments often lead to delays and misclassification. Artificial Intelligence (AI), particularly Machine Learning (ML) and Deep Learning (DL), has transformed diagnostics by enabling data-driven, personalized approaches. This systematic review comprehensively examines AI applications for hormonal disorders, covering supervised ML (e.g., Support Vector Machine, Random Forests), DL architectures (Convolutional Neural Networks, Long Short-Term Memory), and hybrid models enhanced with optimization techniques (Genetic Algorithms, Particle Swarm Optimization). Critical feature selection methods (filter, wrapper, embedded) and hyperparameter tuning strategies (Bayesian Optimization, Grid Search) are analyzed to improve model performance, with studies achieving up to 98% accuracy in PCOS detection and 95% sensitivity in thyroid classification. Publicly available datasets (UCI, Kaggle, clinical repositories) and preprocessing methods for imbalanced data (Synthetic Minority Over-Sampling Technique, Adaptive Synthetic Sampling) are evaluated, alongside Explainable AI (XAI) tools (SHapley Additive Explanations, Local Interpretable Model-agnostic Explanations) to ensure clinical interpretability. Challenges such as data heterogeneity, privacy concerns, and the need for multi-institutional collaboration are discussed, with solutions like federated learning and synthetic data generation proposed. Emerging trends include wearable-enabled real-time monitoring and physiology-informed hybrid models. By synthesizing advancements and limitations, this systematic review highlights AI’s potential to revolutionize hormonal disorder diagnosis while advocating for robust validation and ethical AI deployment in precision endocrinology.
