TY  - JOUR
TI  - Recent Advances in Computational and Machine-Learning Approaches for Alzheimer’s Disease Classification: A Comprehensive Review
AU  - Mahsa Moraveji, Najme Mansouri
T2  - Archives of Computational Methods in Engineering
AB  - Alzheimer’s Disease (AD) is a significant global health challenge, yet the rapid growth of computational research has created a fragmented literature, making it difficult to assess the clinical readiness of proposed models. This systematic review provides a clear synthesis of recent literature (January 2023–March 2025) by critically evaluating 91 peer-reviewed studies. The analysis systematically compares these studies across four key dimensions: (1) datasets and data modalities; (2) computational architectures; (3) performance metrics; and (4) validation rigor. This comparison reveals several critical trends. Analysis shows a heavy reliance on the Alzheimer’s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) dataset, while challenges in multimodal integration persist. Architecturally, Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) remain the dominant approach, with nascent adoption of advanced models like Vision Transformers. While the reported performance for these models is often high—frequently exceeding 95% accuracy on simplified binary tasks—these findings are undermined by weak validation methods. A critical validation gap exists, as the vast majority of studies rely exclusively on internal validation, with very few testing their models on independent datasets and none performing prospective clinical evaluations. This combination of homogenous data, simplified tasks, and non-robust validation limits the applicability of current findings. Consequently, a significant disconnect exists between reported performance and true clinical generalizability. To bridge this research-to-practice gap, future work must adhere to higher research standards. This includes prioritizing diverse datasets through methods like privacy-preserving federated learning, mandating external validation, and integrating explainable AI (XAI) as a core principle to build trustworthy and clinically useful diagnostic tools for Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI) and AD.
DA  - 2025///
PY  - 2025
