TI  - From image classification to segmentation: a comprehensive empirical review
AU  - Ruksana, M. F. Mridha, Jamin Rahman Jim, Md Jonair Hossain, Aritra Das, Md Mohsin Kabir
T2  - Iran Journal of Computer Science
AB  - With the development of the machine learning age, deep learning techniques for computer vision tasks use real-world data to analyze problems across various fields. In particular, it has achieved significant success in image classification, segmentation, and detection on different datasets. As the area of deep learning expands, annotated datasets can be challenging owing to various factors such as the labeling process or difficulty in correctly classifying data, even for experts. Therefore, an extensive survey of machine learning techniques is introduced. Through empirical analysis, several deep learning architectures were applied to benchmark datasets, such as ImageNet, CIFAR-10, COCO, and MNIST. This study includes Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN), Recurrent Neural Networks (RNN), and their variants in these datasets. Additionally, this work reviews the experimental results from modern studies and explains the methodological nuances and comparative performance. In addition to examining the relevance of model performance to preprocessing techniques, various evaluation metrics and promising challenges with future directions for new frontiers are also discussed. Subsequently, this research investigation addresses challenges such as dataset characteristics, model complexity, and computational efficiency and provides insights into the practical implementation of deep learning solutions for real-world applications.
