AB  - The objective of this study is to investigate the predictive performance of various machine learning and deep learning models for blood glucose levels, with an emphasis on their application to simulated dataset (T1DMS) and real-world dataset (OhioT1DM). This research involves the construction and evaluation of deep learning models, including Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM), Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU), and Transformer, alongside traditional machine learning models such as Ridge Regression, Random Forest, and Light Gradient Boosting Machine (LightGBM). Through this systematic analysis, the study assesses the strengths and limitations of these algorithms in short-term blood glucose prediction tasks. The findings indicate that the LSTM model excels in prediction accuracy when managing complex dynamics of blood glucose changes, showing exceptional performance on real dataset. Its advanced feature extraction capabilities render it significantly more effective than other traditional approaches. This study affirms the high accuracy and adaptability of deep learning architectures in intricate scenarios and provides crucial technical support for the development of personalized diabetes management strategies. By advancing this research, it is anticipated to drive innovation in more efficient and safer diabetes management, ultimately enhancing clinical outcomes and the quality of life for patients.
