TY  - CHAP
TI  - Extending Fairness in Single-Cell AI: Evaluating Age, Sex, and Ethnicity Bias with Synthetic Data Augmentation
AU  - Peralta Castro, Fernando
AU  - Zhang, Jiaqi
AU  - Singh, Ritambhara
T2  - Proceedings of the 16th ACM International Conference on Bioinformatics, Computational Biology, and Health Informatics
AB  - Artificial intelligence (AI) increasingly drives critical decisions in healthcare. Yet, many single-cell AI models, including scGPT and Geneformer, are trained on datasets that do not fully represent all ethnic groups, age ranges, or sexes. This imbalance can lead models to learn hidden biases that distort gene expression analysis and contribute to diagnostic errors that disproportionately impact underrepresented populations. These risks are particularly concerning as single-cell technologies become increasingly adopted in research and clinical practice.Despite advances in computational biology, limited research has examined how dataset imbalance introduces subtle demographic patterns into AI systems. This project investigates the extent of demographic bias by applying a measurement called Inverse Local Inverse Simpson's Index (iLISI), which evaluates how well cells from different groups are mixed together in the model's learned representations after training. iLISI produces a numeric score that shows whether the model has unintentionally learned to separate cells based on factors such as ethnicity, age, or sex. For example, in one analysis, we found that cells from Hispanic donors clustered separately from those of non-Hispanic donors, suggesting that the model encoded demographic information unrelated to biological function. Preliminary results indicate that models trained primarily on data from a few dominant groups tend to perform substantially worse on samples from other populations, reducing their ability to generalize and increasing the risk of biased predictions.To address this challenge, we explore the use of scDesign3 to generate synthetic single-cell data that augments real datasets and improves representation across demographic categories. This approach creates simulated cells that maintain the statistical characteristics of real samples while balancing the distribution of under-represented groups. In controlled experiments, introducing synthetic data significantly improved mixing metrics and reduced demographic-specific clustering in the embedding space.These findings are especially relevant for diagnostic AI tools that rely on single-cell gene expression data or digital microscopy systems to classify disease states, including models designed for deployment in low-resource settings where demographic diversity is high and data scarcity is common.By systematically evaluating how training distributions influence model behavior and testing interventions to mitigate bias, this work aims to establish best practices for data curation and model development in single-cell analysis. Ultimately, this research highlights the importance of designing models that accurately reflect diverse populations to ensure that the benefits of AI are shared fairly across all patient groups.
