TI  - HACED: Hierarchical Anatomically Constrained Expression Dictionaries for Autism Prediction
AU  - Li, Caden
AU  - Luo, Xin
T3  - SHWID '25
AB  - Autism spectrum disorder (ASD) screening from facial behavior needs features that are accurate, robust, and understandable to clinicians. Existing systems either depend on manual Facial Action Coding System (FACS) labels, which are costly and sparse, or on deep embeddings that hide which facial regions drive predictions. We propose HACED (Hierarchical Anatomically Constrained Expression Dictionaries), which learns a sparse dictionary over 3D morphable model (3DMM) expression parameters. HACED organizes global and local atoms in a coarse-to-fine hierarchy linked to anatomically defined facial regions, and uses an anatomy-aware regularizer to encourage spatially local, physiologically plausible components. The resulting sparse codes drive a simple ASD classifier and can be mapped back to faces and AU-like patterns for inspection. We evaluate HACED in a 3DMM-based experimental setting with three controlled ablation studies that vary dictionary capacity, anatomy-prior strength, and spatial resolution. Across these studies we measure reconstruction error, AU coverage, ASD classification area under the ROC curve (AUC), an interpretability score, and robustness to noise and occlusions. Moderate-capacity, anatomically constrained dictionaries at high spatial resolution achieve the best trade-off: they reach an ASD AUC of 0.566 at K = 50, while larger unconstrained dictionaries overfit and become harder to interpret. These results show that anatomically structured dictionaries can bridge clinical interpretability and machine performance. HACED provides a practical, transparent feature layer for ASD risk screening, especially in telemedicine settings where robustness and traceability are essential.
