TI  - From Prediction to Prescription: Bridging Management Science and Frontier Machine Learning
AU  - Yin, Wanlong
T3  - ICCBD '25
AB  - Modern ML excels at prediction, but operational decisions must also satisfy safety, capacity, fairness, and budget constraints. We introduce a decision-centric, modular workflow that couples doubly robust causal estimation, distributionally robust optimization, and safe reinforcement learning, alongside interpretability and governance. We derive a conservative policy-improvement test using high-confidence off-policy evaluation (HCOPE) and validate it on dynamic pricing and inventory control with demand substitution. In semi-synthetic studies, the approach yields consistent reward gains (+15% over myopic; +2–7% over nominal RL/DRO/HCOPE), reduces violations to 0.018 ± 0.01, and improves robustness to 0.92 ± 0.03 (across 10 seeds), while producing concise, auditable rationales. Taken together, these results chart a practical path to embedding ML in high-stakes, operations-intensive settings.
