TI  - Dental Health Center Performance Dashboard with Mixed Integer Linear Programming (MILP)-Based Appointment Scheduling
AU  - Barlis, Mikka
AU  - Resuello, Geldof
T3  - ICBIM '25
AB  - This study developed and validated a web-based business analytics solution for a Philippine SME dental clinic, built using Python, Flask, SQLite, Pandas, Plotly, and PuLP-CBC (Coin-OR Branch and Cut). The development of the system was guided by an analysis of the clinic's strategic gaps, which highlighted challenges in performance monitoring and appointment management. The system enables stakeholders to visualize ten (10) key performance indicators (KPIs) and optimize dentist working hours within real-world constraints through the MILP model. The MILP model was evaluated using both simulated data, generated through random stratified sampling for training, and real-world data for testing. It achieved up to 88.75% dentist utilization in simulations and 79.9% in practice, with a fairness index of up to 0.86. Scheduling success rates were primarily influenced by real clinic capacity rather than system error. Any unscheduled requests were traceable to resource limits and constraints. Pearson correlation coefficient analysis supported this, showing a strong positive correlation (r = 0.90) between appointment requests and unscheduled appointments, confirming that higher demand leads to more unscheduled cases. Strong negative correlations were also found: (r = -0.86) between total requests and success rate, and (r = -0.99) between unscheduled appointments and success rate, highlighting that resource limitations, not algorithmic or model error, account for lower scheduling rates. The model consistently produced “optimal” solver results across all requests, demonstrating its effectiveness in appointment allocation. User Acceptance Testing (UAT) and System Usability Scale (SUS) assessments showed perfect task success rates and a mean SUS score of 91.25. Overall, the solution significantly improved KPI monitoring and appointment management. Future recommendations include integration with electronic health records, the addition of predictive analytics, and broader cross-clinic adoption.
